<TITLE> Monsoon depression deepens </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, June 28 (bdnews24.com)- The monsoon depression over the west central areas of the Bay of Bengal and the adjoining northwest Bay area has moved rapidly northwards. It intensified into a deep depression and now lies over the northwest Bay and adjoining west central Bay. Squally and stormy winds may blow over coastal areas as a result, according to a weathercast. Met official Sarwar Alam told bdnews24.com, "The depression was centered about 760km southwest of Chittagong port, 715km south-west of Cox's Bazar port and 590km south-south west of Mongla port at 12pm Thursday." The depression is likely to intensify further while moving in a north/northwesterly direction. Under this influence steep pressure gradients will persists over the north Bay. A special Met office forecast directed Chittagong, Cox's Bazar and Mongla seaports to hoist local cautionary signal No. 3. All fishing boats and trawlers on the north Bay of Bengal have been advised to remain near the coast and stay vigilant. Gusts and squalls with a wind speed of between 40kph to 60kph will be experienced within 48km of the depression centre. Sea conditions will remain moderate. bdnew
